{"label":"Stories","id":"stories-4","lockAfter":3,"list":[{"id":"100","type":"passage","label":"The Four Friends","data":{"title":"The Four Friends","text":"Long ago, three friends, a deer, a crow, and a mouse,  lived in a jungle. They used to share their meals.\nOne day, a turtle came to them and said, \"I also want to be your friend. I'm all alone.\"\n\"You're most welcome,\" said the crow. \"But, what about your safety, there are many hunters around. They visit this jungle regularly. Suppose, a hunter comes, how will you save yourself?\"\n\"That is the reason why I want to join your group,\" said the turtle.\nNo sooner had they talked about it, a hunter appeared on the scene. Seeing the hunter, the deer darted away; the crow flew in the sky and the mouse ran into a hole. The turtle tried to crawl away fast, but he was caught by the hunter. The hunter tied him up in the net. He was sad to lose the deer. But he thought, it was better to feast on the turtle rather than returning hungry.\nThe turtle's three friends got worried. They sat together to think of some plan to free their friend from the hunter's snare.\nThe crow, then, flew high up in the sky and spotted the hunter walking by the river bank. As planned, the deer ran ahead of the hunter unnoticed and laid on the hunter's path as if dead.\nThe hunter saw the deer from a distance, lying on the ground. He was very happy to have found it again. \"Now I'll have a good feast on it and sell its beautiful skin in the market,\" thought the hunter.  He put down the turtle on the ground and ran to pick up the deer.\nIn the meantime, the mouse gnawed through the net and freed the turtle. The turtle hurriedly crawled away into the river water.\nUnaware of the plot of these friends, the hunter went to fetch the deer for its tasty flesh and beautiful skin. But, what he saw with his mouth wide open was that, when he reached near, the deer suddenly sprang up to its feet and darted away into the jungle. Before he could understand anything, the deer disappeared.\nDejected, the hunter turned back to collect the turtle he had left behind on the ground in the snare. But he was shocked to see the snare lying nibbled at and the turtle missing. For a moment, the hunter thought that he was dreaming. But the damaged snare lying on the ground was proved that he was very much awake and he was compelled to believe that some miracle had taken place.\nThe hunter got frightened on account of these happenings and ran out of the jungle. The four friends once again started living happily."}},{"id":"200","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"Who was the fourth friend to join?","options":"A turtle, A crow, A deer, A mouse"},{"qText":"What was the hunter's main target?","options":"deer, turtle, crow, mouse"},{"qText":"Who freed the turtle from the nets?","options":"mouse, deer, turtle, crow"},{"qText":"In what way, the crow helped to rescue the turtle?","options":"It flew high and spotted the location of the hunter.\nIt did not help.\nIt helped by making lot of noise."},{"qText":"At the end of the story, the hunter was _______.","options":"disappointed, angry, happy, tired"}]}},{"id":"300","label":"Order the sentences","type":"sorting","data":{"title":"Order the sentences based on the story.","text":"Seeing the hunter, the three friends escaped fast.\nBut the turtle was unable to move fast.\nThe hunter tied the turtle in a net.\nThe three friends planned to free the turtle.\nThe deer tried to divert the hunter.\nWhen the hunter was away, the mouse freed the turtle from the net."}},{"id":"400","type":"passage","label":"The Mice that Ate Balance","data":{"img":{"url":"story/24_mice_ate_balance.jpg"},"title":"The Mice that Ate Balance","text":"Once upon a time, there lived a wealthy merchant, in a village. He ran a big business. His village was situated near a river. Once, due to heavy rain, the river was flooded. One night, the whole village was submerged in neck-deep water. The crops, houses, and factories in the village were destroyed and hundreds of people and cattle perished in the flood.\nThe merchant had to suffer heavy losses in his business. He decided to shift to some other town to try his luck. He planned to earn a lot of money and then come back to his native village to start his business again.\nThe merchant had a heavy iron balance. It belonged to his ancestors. He couldn't carry such a heavy thing along with him. So, before starting on his journey, he decided to keep this ancestral item with his friend Ravi. He met Ravi and requested him, \"My friend, as you know, I'm leaving for some distant place to earn money, so that I could start my business once again when I come back. I have an old iron balance with me. Will you please keep it safe with you till I return?\"\nRavi readily agreed to his friend's request and said, \"Don't worry, I'll keep it safe for you. You can take it back after you return.\" The merchant thanked Ravi for his helping attitude. He left the iron balance with Ravi and left for some other distant town.\nA few years passed. By this time, the merchant had done good business and had earned a lot of money. He returned to his native village and went to his friend's house to meet him. Ravi showed his happiness in meeting the merchant. Both of them talked for hours. When it was time to leave, the merchant asked his friend to return his iron balance. At this, Ravi looked sad and said, \"Friend, I am sorry but I don't have your balance with me anymore. There are a lot of mice in my house. They ate it up.\"\nThe merchant was surprised to hear Ravi's explanation. 'How can mice eat iron,' he thought to himself, but apparently, he said something different, \"Don't feel sorry, Ravi. The mice have always proved a menace to everyone. Let us forget about it.\"\n\"Yes,\" Ravi said. \"This is the only way out.\" He was happy that the merchant believed his words. This was because he expected a lot of heated arguments in this respect.\nWhile taking leave from his friend, the merchant said to Ravi, \"I'm going to temple to make an offering of laddoos. Could you please send your son with me? I would like to send some laddoos for you also. He would also look after my shoes outside the temple while I offer prayers inside.\nRavi asked his son to go with the merchant. Then, the merchant, instead of taking Ravi's son to the temple, took him to a nearby hill and tied him with a big rock, and came back home.\nWhen Ravi didn't see his son return, he asked the merchant where his son was. \"I'm sorry,\" said the merchant. \"While your son was looking after my shoes outside the temple, a big vulture swooped down upon him and carried him away.\"\n\"What nonsense!\" shouted Ravi. \"How can a vulture carry off a young boy?\" But the merchant repeatedly claimed that a vulture carried away Ravi's son. The argument reached such a point that they began quarreling with each other, using bad words.\nUltimately the matter had to be taken to the court. The Judge listened to both the parties and ordered the merchant to bring Ravi's son to court, otherwise, he would be sent to jail.\n\"My Lord\", said the merchant, \"How can I, when a vulture has already carried away the boy?\"\n\"Shut up!\" the judge reprimanded the merchant. \"How can a bird carry away a young boy?\"\n\"It can, my lord,\" said the merchant. \"If mice can eat my iron balance, why can't a bird carry away a grown-up boy?\" Then he narrated the whole story to the judge.\nThe judge then warned Ravi to tell the truth or he would be imprisoned. At last, Ravi admitted his guilt. The judge ordered him to return the iron balance to the merchant and the merchant to give back Ravi's son."}},{"id":"500","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"To whom did the merchant give his ancestral property?","options":"To his friend, To his servant, To his neighbor, To his relative"},{"qText":"Why did the merchant leave his village?","options":"Due to heavy loss in his business\nFor a pilgrimage trip\nTo meet one of his friends"},{"qText":"What happened when the merchant asked his friend to return the iron balance?","options":"He said that mice ate the iron balance.\nHe said that he lost his iron balance.\nHe honestly returned the iron balance."},{"qText":"True or False: Mice can eat an iron balance.","options":"False, True"},{"qText":"True or False: Vulture cannot carry a grown-up boy.","options":"True, False"},{"qText":"Who was selfish and tried to cheat in this story?","options":"Ravi, Merchant, Judge, Boy"}]}},{"id":"600","label":"Order the sentences","type":"sorting","data":{"title":"Order the sentences based on the story.","text":"Once, there lived a wealthy merchant.\nDue to the flood, he lost most of this wealth.\nHe decided to temporarily move to another place to develop his business.\nHe met his old friend, before leaving the village.\nHe asked his friend to keep his iron balance for some time."}},{"id":"700","type":"passage","label":"The Well Dispute","data":{"title":"The Well Dispute","img":{"url":"story/26_well_dispute.jpg"},"text":"Once there was a complaint at King Akbar's court. Two neighbours shared their garden. In that garden, there was a well that was possessed by Iqbal Khan. His neighbor, who was a farmer wanted to buy the well for irrigation purposes. Therefore, they signed an agreement between them, after which the farmer-owned the well.\nEven after selling the well to the farmer, Iqbal continued to fetch water from the well. Angered by this, the farmer had come to get justice from King Akbar. King Akbar asked Iqbal the reason for fetching water from the well even after selling it to the farmer. Iqbal replied that he sold only the well to the farmer but not the water inside it.\nKing Akbar wanted Birbal, who was present in the court listening to the problem, to solve the dispute. Birbal came forward and gave a solution. He said, \"Iqbal, You say that you have sold only the well to the farmer. And you claim that the water is yours. Then how come you can keep your water inside another person's well without paying rent?\"\nIqbal's trickery was countered. The farmer got justice and Birbal was fairly rewarded."}},{"id":"800","label":"Multiple Choice Questions - MCQ","type":"mcq","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"From whom did the farmer buy the well?","options":"Iqbal Khan, Akbar, Birbal"},{"qText":"Why did the farmer buy the well?","options":"For irrigation, For drinking, For washing"},{"qText":"What was Iqbal's statement in the court?","options":"He sold only the well and not the water in it.\nHe didn't sell the well.\nHe didn't get the money from the farmer."},{"qText":"Who did the farmer approach for justice?","options":"Akbar, Birbal, Court"},{"qText":"How did Birbal solve the case?","options":"He asked Iqbal to pay rent for water.\nHe asked Iqbal to take away his water.\nHe asked Iqbal to continue using the water."}]}},{"id":"900","label":"Order the sentences","type":"sorting","data":{"title":"Order the sentences based on the story.","text":"The farmer approached the king, with a case against Iqbal.\nHe told the king that he bought the well from Iqbal.\nBut Iqbal continued to use the water after selling it.\nIqbal cunningly said that he sold only the well and not the water in it.\nConfused king, redirected the case to Birbal."}},{"id":"1000","type":"passage","label":"Stone Soup","data":{"title":"Stone Soup","text":"Some travelers came to a village, carrying nothing more than an empty cooking pot. On their arrival, the villagers were not willing to share any of their food with the hungry travelers. Then, the travelers went to a stream and filled the pot with water, dropped a large stone in it, and placed it over a fire.\nOne of the villagers became curious and asked what they were doing. The travelers answered that they were making \"stone soup\", which tasted wonderful and which they would be delighted to share with the villager, although it still needed a little bit of garnish, which they were missing, to improve the flavor.\nThe villager, who wanted to get a share of the soup, did not mind parting with a few carrots. So they were added to the soup. Another villager walked by, inquiring about the pot, and the travelers again mentioned their stone soup which had not yet reached its full potential.\nThe villager handed them a little bit of seasoning. More and more villagers walked by, each adding another ingredient. Finally, the stone (being inedible) was removed from the pot, and a delicious and nourishing pot of soup was enjoyed by the travelers and villagers.\nThough the travelers tricked the villagers into sharing their food with them, they have successfully transformed it into a tasty and nutritious meal which they shared with the donors."}},{"id":"1100","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What did the travelers carry?","options":"An empty cooking pot.\nA pot full of food.\nA bag full of clothes.\nThey did not carry anything."},{"qText":"How did the villagers react to the travelers?","options":"The villagers did not share food with them.\nThe villagers did not allow them inside their village.\nThe villagers shared their food."},{"qText":"What was the first ingredient added to the soup?","options":"A large stone, A pinch of salt, Carrot"},{"qText":"The travellers prepared the soup using ________.","options":"the ingredients supplied by the villagers, the stone, black magic"},{"qText":"How did the villagers feel at the end?","options":"They were happy.\nThey were sad.\nThey were angry.\nThey were disappointed."}]}},{"id":"1200","label":"Order the Sentences","type":"sorting","data":{"title":"Order the sentences based on the story.","text":"Some travelers reached a village having nothing except a cooking pot.\nThey were hungry.\nBut the villagers were not willing to share their food with them.\nThe travelers silently placed the pot filled with water over the fire.\nAnd they dropped a big stone into the boiling water.\nThe villagers got curious about the stone soup."}},{"id":"1300","type":"passage","label":"The Man and the Tree","data":{"img":{"url":"story/28_tree.jpg"},"title":"The Man and the Tree","text":"One day, a man climbed up a tree. While climbing up, he did not realize how tall the tree was and kept climbing up. On reaching the top, when the man looked down, he realized that climbing down from the tree would not be as easy as climbing up. He could not think of any way of getting down without injuring himself seriously.\nHe asked the people who were passing by to help him.  But nobody could think of any way to bring him down safely. Soon, quite a few people gathered around the tree and tried to help the man, but no one knew what to do. The man remained stuck on top of the tree.\nJust then, Mulla, who was walking by, saw this scene and wondered what was going on. The people standing around the tree told Mulla about the situation. “Oh!” Mulla said, “I’ll get him down in no time.” He took a long rope and threw one end of it up to the man telling him to tie the rope around his waist.\nEveryone wondered what Mulla’s plan was. When one of them asked him, Mulla replied, “Just leave it to me. It’s a great plan.”\nWhen the man on the tree had tied the rope tightly around his waist, Mulla pulled the rope with all his force. As soon as Mulla did this, the man fell from the tree and hurt himself badly. The bystanders were shocked. They turned to Mulla and asked, “What did you do? What a silly plan you had!”\nMulla replied, “Well, once I did exactly the same thing and saved someone’s life.” One man asked him, “Is that true?” “Absolutely!” replied Mulla, “The only difference was I saved him from a well and not a tree.”"}},{"id":"1400","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"Where did the man climb?","options":"A tree, A hill, A building,  A ladder"},{"qText":"The man was sad because ______ .","options":"He didn't know how to climb down.\nHe was tired of climbing the tree.\nHe was thirsty.\nPeople from the ground laughed at him."},{"qText":"How the passing by people reacted to the man's call for help?","options":"They gathered around the tree and tried to help.\nThey scolded the man for climbing the tree.\nThey waited for Mulla to come and help.\nThey ran away."},{"qText":"Who came forward to help the man?","options":"Mulla, Birbal, Tenali"},{"qText":"What did Mulla take to bring the man down?","options":"A rope, A ladder, An Axe, A piece of cloth"},{"qText":"What was the result of Mulla's attempt?","options":"unsuccessful, successful"}]}},{"id":"1500","label":"Order the Sentences","type":"sorting","data":{"title":"Order the sentences based on the story.","text":"One day, a man climbed up a tree.\nOn reaching the top, he didn't know how to climb down.\nHe asked for help from people who were passing by.\nThey gathered around the tree and tried to help.\nBut they don't know how to help him."}}]}